</span></p><p>After years of improvement, Nag finalized the script in 1980. He simplified the alphabet and selected 27 standard letters for regular use.</p><p>In the same year, he presented the script to the then Chief Minister of Odisha, J. B. Patnaik.</p><p>He also submitted a formal memorandum requesting constitutional recognition for the Munda language. This was an important step toward official acceptance.</p><p>---</p><p><span style=\"font-weight: bold; color: rgb(27, 67, 50);\">1999 – National Appeal</span></p><p>In 1999, Rohidas Singh Nag and other activists submitted a memorandum to the President of India. They requested that the Mundari language be granted constitutional recognition.</p><p>This showed that Nag was not only a script inventor but also a strong advocate for language rights and indigenous recognition at the national level.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Educational and Cultural Impact</span></h2><p>By 2004, several schools in Odisha had started using Mundari Bani for teaching. This helped:</p><p></p><ul><li>Promote mother-tongue education</li><li>Preserve cultural heritage</li><li>Encourage written literature in Mundari</li></ul><p></p><p>The script became a symbol of pride and identity for the Munda community.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Digital Recognition</span></h2><p>The script, also known as Nag Mundari, was officially added to the Unicode Standard in 2021–2022. This inclusion allows the script to be used in digital platforms, computers, and smartphones.</p><p>This ensured that Mundari Bani entered the modern digital era.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Legacy</span></h2><p>Rohidas Singh Nag passed away on 30 December 2012 at the age of 78. However, his contribution continues to influence language preservation movements.</p><p>Today, he is remembered as:</p><p></p><ul><li>The inventor of Mundari Bani</li><li>A protector of tribal linguistic heritage</li><li>A leader in the Mundari language movement</li></ul><p></p><p>His work remains one of the most important achievements in the history of indigenous languages in India.</p><p>---</p>"
